        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(azure): fork windows leases from snapshots",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- add direct Azure Windows OS-disk checkpoints and snapshot-backed forks\n- require explicit `--no-reboot=false`, deallocate for a consistent snapshot, then restart the source VM\n- rotate SSH host keys, SSH login, Windows login, and TightVNC service credentials on each fork\n- preserve loopback-only VNC and carry the snapshot subscription, resource group, region, and OS type into the fork\n- document the disruptive checkpoint contract and managed-disk requirement\n\n## Why\n\nPrepared Azure Windows desktop leases are expensive to bootstrap repeatedly. A native OS-disk snapshot gives later leases a fast starting point, but only if the fork is treated as a new machine: identity and access credentials must rotate, VNC must remain tunnel-only, and Azure resource scope must follow the snapshot.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `go test ./internal/providers/azure ./internal/cli`\n- `go vet ./...`\n- `go test -race ./...` (one unrelated timing-sensitive WSL2 marker test failed under the full parallel run; it passed immediately in isolation with `-race -count=1`)\n- autoreview: clean after fixes for source restart, subscription propagation, VNC service credential rotation, and Linux snapshot OS-type preservation\n\n## Live Azure proof\n\nPending coordinator capacity. The first attempt waited 30 minutes without a server assignment; the current retry is recorded separately when it completes. No live success is claimed until a VM is assigned and the create/fork/credential/tunnel checks pass.\n",
